The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | City base for London bank
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      City base for London bank
          SOUNAK MITRA                              
	Calcutta, April 14: Duncan Lawrie, the London-based private banking arm of Camellia Plc, plans to make Calcutta the base for its Asian operations.        
	The wholly owned subsidiary of Camellia opened its first representative office outside the UK in the city yesterday after getting the Reserve Bank of Indias approval.         
	Duncan Lawrie will operate from Goodrickes head office in Calcutta. Camellia holds a 74 per cent stake in tea plantation firm Goodricke Group.        
	India is our top priority. We hope our historic affinity with the region and our client-centric approach will provide a viable option for successful individuals and their families looking to diversify their investment portfolios, Phil Degan, investment director of Duncan Lawrie Asset Management Ltd, said.        
	According to Duncan Lawrie managing director Peter Field, the bank will also explore other Asian countries after securing a good clientele in India. Everything in this part of the globe will be done from our Calcutta office. We dont have any plan to set up any establishments in any other Asian country, Field said.        
	Duncan Lawrie will offer portfolio management services to Indians willing to invest in the international markets, including the UK and the US. We are looking at $200,000 per annum investments from each Indian client, Alan M. Molloy, managing director of Duncan Lawrie (IOM) Ltd, said.        
	The Calcutta office will offer liaison services for general queries, access to investment managers via telephone and emails and also face-to-face meetings.        
	Clients will be offered tailor-made portfolio that suits each individual. We include every possible investment opportunities in both developed and developing economies, depending on clients risk-taking capabilities, Degan said.        
	The portfolios of the Indian clients will be managed from Duncan Lawries head office in London.        
	The bank offers client-specific services, with an emphasis on personal relationship, to high net worth individuals.                                                                                                                                       
